<DOC><DOCNO> AP890526-0178 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-05-26-89 2134EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-PlaneCrash     05-26 0284</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Plane Crash,0292</SECOND><HEAD>Two Dead, Three Injured In Plane Crash</HEAD><BYLINE>By BETH HARRIS</BYLINE><BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE><DATELINE>GREENWOOD, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   An airplane carrying race fans from SouthDakota to the Indianapolis 500 crashed in a softball field Friday,killing two aboard and injuring three others.   The plane, a twin-engine Beechcraft Baron, crashed at about 2:30p.m. after the pilot notified the Indianapolis InternationalAirport he was having ``serious fuel problems,'' said BarbaraDettmer, a spokeswoman for the Federal Aviation Administration inChicago.   FAA and National Transportation Safety Board officials were atthe scene investigating the cause of the crash.   Johnson County Sheriff Doran Miller said the plane was headingfor Indianapolis, 11 miles north of Greenwood, for the Indianapolis500 on Sunday. The flight originated in Sioux Falls, S.D.   The two victims were identified as Robert Best, 69, and WarrenE. Schoon, 68, both of Sioux Falls, S.D. Miller said both men werethrown from the plane.   Two other passengers, Arnold Tofteland, 60, of Luverne, Minn.,and Ross Fenn, 62, of Sioux Falls, S.D., were taken to Indianapolishospitals in critical condition. The pilot, Larry Larson, 29, ofSioux Falls, was in serious but stable condition at UniversityHeights Hospital, a spokesman said.   One witness, Max Maddox, said he was on a nearby golf course andwatched the plane crash in a softball field behind the CommunityChurch of Greenwood.   ``It had no power. The propellers were just fanning in the wind.I kept watching him drop and drop, and then I saw some smoke,''Maddox said.   The plane was attempting to make an emergency landing at theGreenwood Municipal Airport when it crashed about four miles away,said airport spokesman Aaron Pietras.</TEXT></DOC>